rComments: give wrong answers very misleading from time to time
Great class but assignments and exercises are very difficult, and TAs are not that helpful

Initially started out loving the course and appreciating the content and its delivery. Lectures were great fun to attend and David made it relatable and easy to digest. Halfway through, a 180 degree turn and things just got very difficult to grasp and he was not helpful at all during office hours. His quality of teaching just kept depreciating.
Great personality but impossible finals. It is frustrating to have studied for 40 hours and cant do his past test.

He explains concepts well in lectures, but the difficulty of the course is deceptively inconsistent. It gets progressively harder, and his final exams are so difficult that some might argue they are unfair. I've also seen him cut people off quite rudely during office hours.
teacherRatingTags: ['Lots of homework', 'Get ready to read', 'Test heavy']

rComments: Great teacher. His explanations are straight forward and gives real life example to help you understand.

David is amazing at teaching and seems nice during the entire semester, but once you get to the final, David shows his true colors. He frequently writes finals that are impossible to finish in the allotted time as well stuff that hasn't really been taught. You should probably avoid if you need a decent grade in his course.
David is the best instructor I have in my first year at university! He is very approachable and he would also like to help me with problems outside of course range! He is indeed a very good person!!!

David's background with formal teaching training is visible. He is one of the best profs teaching wise that I have had so far. However, his grading criteria is a little unfair and not available at all, he is my favourite prof.

Not realistic in terms of workload for a first-year course. I understand, he puts a lot of emphasis on each topic. However, the workload in this course without a doubt was the highest among all my courses. The assignments are challenging and require you to start the day it is released. Great course to put a huge amount of stress on first years.

Had him twice for CSC165 and CSC324. He is a lot more approachable and nicer to his students during office hours when I took CSC324. He explains things very well in class, but his assignments are very hard and confusing. His slides are pretty useless so don't skip class. I had a much more pleasant experience with David Liu in CSC324 than in CSC165.
teacherRatingTags: ['Lots of homework', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Tough grader']

rComments: David's an amazing prof tasked with handling difficult courses, especially considering they're typically taken by first year students. In lecture, he's very thorough in his explanations and present material in a manner that is digest-able. He understands how much he needs to give students while still leaving enough for them to learn on their own.
teacherRatingTags: ['Participation matters', 'Amazing lectures', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: Bad.
I really like his notes on CSC165. These notes helped me signitificantly on developing good understanding in the subject.
One of the best CS profs in UofT. Very clear with his explanations and approachable after class!

Really nice guy, and cares a lot about his students. Computer science is a difficult subject, but he manages to make it straightforward and engaging. Make sure to go to his office hours and ask him questions in person. He is very helpful and you will benefit a lot!
His tests are tough, but his notes have saved my ass in multiple courses. He explains everything so well. Worth checking out his notes for 236, 263, and 324.

That yellow smiley face tie he wears, esp for exam days. Honestly one of the most helpful profs I've ever had. The course itself can be challenging but his teaching method made it extremely straightforward. When he explains the material, everything just suddenly makes sense. If you are confused, make sure you ask, guaranteed to make a difference.

His courses are really well organized. His lectures are usually easy to follow, while he would provide you insightful questions to solidify your understanding (even on tests/exams). Make sure you do the questions he gave you as you will always learn something new from each one of them.

Was really good teacher and enthusiastic. Retaking this course, and he was much better than Fairgrieve. Read negative comments about his office hours, but can't say anything on that as I never went to his. He seemed okay when I asked him questions in lecture though.
best first year prof i've had by a pretty big margin. thanks david!
lectures are good but that doesn't make up for the insane difficulty. needs to know that the students are not at the same intellectual level as him.
teacherRatingTags: ['Gives good feedback', 'Tough grader', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: His lectures are good, but at office hours he is rude. He kicked people out during office hours if you have too many questions. When you ask him a question, he says "this is your job to do". He makes you look dumb and worthless. Not approachable at all, and would never see him for office hours again
He is one of the greatest professors I meet at UofT.  Questions are welcomed in his lecture and he is very patient to answer your questions.
His lectures are really thorough and reading his notes beforehand would make his explanations much clearer.
Great lectures, really helpful in class and outside on Piazza/office hours. Pretty funny and laid-back as well. Easily my favourite prof in the department so far, maybe on par with Sam.
David Liu is excellent. His lectures were fun and tests/exam were straightforward, too.

He is a diligent lecturer, with an excellent course website. His lectures were clear and conceptual, though his course website is really all you need to understand the material. His assignments can be lengthy, be sure to start early.
Meh,not a good teacher, harsh on marks.

Very good lecturer, but you better hope his lectures are enough: he is very uncomfortable to talk to during office hours and always sounds like he's pissed at you. Tests are fair, but assignments are long.

David was a very good professor. He is fair and explains everything very well.  Any problems that I had were due to the course (way too easy and repetitive) and not David. I would recommend Anyone thinking of taking CSC148 to take it with David

Liu has been so far one of the best prof Ive had at UofT. His lecture are extremely engaging, I felt like every lecture lasted 5 minutes instead of one hour! Midterms were not too hard but assignments are not to be underestimated, start the as early as possible! Quality of my learning experience: 10000. Would be nice to have another course with him

He's not very helpful during office time - sort of expects you to know everything beforehand, which contrasts the actual purpose of the office time; plus, his curriculum outline is very confusing and different from the ones that other proffs use. That added to his bizarre regrade policy and his tough marking criteria, it was a nightmare.

Very interesting course with an amazing lecturer. Do expect a lot of homework, though the homework definitely helps you understand the material and prepares you well for tests. Only complaint would be office hours, he seems like he's annoyed with your questions.
I feel that one of the reasons I did quite well was because of David's teaching.

He took a class that I was dreading and made it clear and interesting. Ended up getting a good mark, would not have otherwise if I had found the material boring. Quite a bit of weekly course work (though they're not too hard), but tests are fair and reflect the work well.

Best teacher I've ever had in my life. He takes teaching really seriously, and he does a really good job it. While he does takes his teaching very seriously, he also somehow keeps a chill vibe going, so you're not afraid to ask him questions.   You've gotta take a class with Liu before you graduate! #uoftbucketlist
Helpful, clear, organized. David is a top lecturer.

Pretty cool proff, really smart and knows what he is talking about. Be wary he is a hard ass. Makes you do a set of problems (not that hard) and challenges (really hard) every week. Do the work and youll be fine.

David's an amazing prof! Lectures are very well delivered, interesting, clear and engaging. He answered my questions well in  office hours. The course is fairly easy but the midterms can be challenging. Assignmentsexercises are easy enough if you put the time into them.

Liu is a good prof but he won't provide too much help to students. If you ask his questions, he prefers yourself to check online or books instead of asking him. But he will give you the hint. But his lecture is pretty good without accent.

His lectures are great, but if you go to his office hours, he is not much help -- he gives short answers to any questions you have and answers the questions as if you are already supposed to know the answer.
He is just an amazing prof!
Really good teacher and made difficult concepts clear

David is a phd student who would teach as good as some senior lecturers and professors. He is really enthusiastic in his teaching and he ensures that he makes his lectures as plausible as possible. He is great in his teaching but he also expects hard work to be handed in when he assigns anything.
lectures are just amazing you have to attend the led
awsome prof. explains material very well. wish i had him for all my cs course
Pretty amazing professor. Even though he is much younger than the other professors he seems to be really good at explaining his points.
